. Challengers filed suit in 2014 against 12 majority-black districts which, they say, were drawn with too much of an emphasis on race. The Supreme Court first addressed the matter in 2017, when it blessed one of the districts and sent the other 11 back to the district court for another look. On reconsideration, and with the replacement of one of the three original judges, the lower court ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"a","attribs":{"href":"https://www.brennancenter.org/sites/default/files/legal-work/BH_v_VABoardofElections_Opinion_06.26.18.pdf"},"children":[{"data":"declared","type":"text"}]},{"data":" all 11 districts unconstitutional. Now the justices will have the final say. ","type":"text"}]},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"If the map is found to violate the constitution’s promise of equal protection of the laws, well, most of the damage has been done. While ","type":"text"},{"type":"tag","name":"em","attribs":{},"children":[{"data":"Bethune-Hill","type":"text"}]},{"data":" was wending its way through the federal judiciary, Virginia used the map for elections in 2011, 2013, 2015 and 2017. With another census coming up in 2020 and a new round of redistricting to follow, the only question is whether the map will have one more go in 2019 before it expires on its own. But such a last hurrah may hold big consequences. Virginia Republicans are clinging to a 51-49 edge in the statehouse; the 2011 map could help them keep it. Meanwhile, a scholar’s alternative map—drawn in late 2018 at the lower-court’s request to fix the infirmities of the 2011 version—could push Democrats over the threshold in this autumn’s election, handing them the chamber and, if they muster a Senate majority too, the cartographer’s pen to redistrict for the coming decade. ","type":"text"}]},{"type":"tag","name":"figure","attribs":{"role":"presentation","itemtype":"https://schema.org/WPAdBlock"},"children":[]},{"type":"tag","name":"p","attribs":{},"children":[{"da